  "prompt": "Where can Typhoons happen and how are they formed?",
  "response": "Typhoons can occur in the Northwest Pacific Ocean, particularly affecting East Asian countries like Japan, China, the Philippines, Taiwan, South Korea, and Vietnam.\n\nTyphoons are formed through a process that involves several key conditions:\n\n1. **Warm Ocean Water**: The sea surface temperature must be at least 26.5\u00b0C (80\u00b0F) to provide the necessary heat and moisture. Warm water causes the surface air to rise and creates a low-pressure area.\n\n2. **Atmospheric Instability**: There must be a sufficient temperature gradient between the surface and the upper atmosphere to sustain convection, which is the rising and sinking of air masses.\n\n3. **High Humidity**: High levels of moisture in the mid to lower troposphere support the development of the storm and allow the intense convection needed.\n\n4. **Low Wind Shear**: Wind shear (difference in wind speed and direction) between the surface and higher altitudes needs to be low. High wind shear can disrupt the development of the cyclonic system.\n\n5. **Pre-existing Disturbance**: Often there needs to be some form of pre-existing disturbance like a cluster of thunderstorms or a tropical wave that serves as a seed for the development of the typhoon.\n\n6. **Coriolis Effect**: This effect, which is due to the Earth\u2019s rotation, helps to spin the weather system and contributes to the cyclonic motion. It is more effective further from the equator.\n\nOnce these conditions come together, they can lead to the development of a typhoon. The storm begins as a tropical depression, strengthens to a tropical storm, and if it continues to gain power, it becomes a typhoon when sustained wind speeds exceed 74 mph (119 km/h).",
